Linux is an open-source operating system that manages computer hardware and software, just like Windows or macOS. It acts as a bridge between applications and the system’s hardware (CPU, memory, disk).

Linux is a free, secure, and powerful operating system widely used in servers, cloud computing, and development environments.

Key Features
Open-source → Anyone can view and modify the code
Secure → Strong permissions and user control
Stable & reliable → Runs servers with minimal crashes
Multi-user & multitasking → Multiple users/programs at once
Customizable → Many versions (distributions)

Popular Linux Distributions
Ubuntu
CentOS
Red Hat Enterprise Linux

Where is Linux Used?
Web servers
Cloud platforms (AWS, Azure)
Mobile (Android is based on Linux)
DevOps and container environments (Docker, Kubernetes)

Interview:
Linux is an open-source operating system that manages hardware and software resources, widely used for servers, cloud computing, and development due to its stability, security, and flexibility.

Difference between Linux and Unix

Linux → An open-source operating system inspired by Unix
Unix → A proprietary (licensed) operating system originally developed in the 1970s (E.g. Mac OS)

Feature	                            Linux	                      Unix
Source Code	                        Open-source	                Mostly closed-source
Cost	                              Free	                      Paid (licensed)
Development	                        Community + companies	      Developed by vendors
Flexibility	                        Highly customizable	        Less flexible
Usage	                              Servers, cloud, DevOps	    Enterprise systems, legacy systems

Linux is an open-source, Unix-like operating system that is free and widely used, while Unix is a proprietary system developed by vendors, typically used in enterprise environments.”
